## Preface to the Seventh Edition

- Book originally written in early 1950s while Heilbroner was a graduate student
  at the **New School for Social Research**
- Inspired by a seminar on **Adam Smith** taught by **Adolph Lowe**
  (who lived to 102 and remained Heilbroner's "warmest and severest critic")
- Title came from **Frederick Lewis Allen**, editor of *Harper's*: Heilbroner
  wanted to call it *The Money Philosophers*; Allen said "you mean 'worldly'"
- Publishers later wanted to rename it *The Great Economists* — fortunately failed
- The 7th edition adds a new organizing thread: the role of **"visions"** —
  pre-analytic worldviews that underlie all social analysis
  - Concept credited to **Josef Schumpeter**, who broached it in the 1950s
  - Heilbroner admits he missed it himself for decades
- Final chapter titled "The End of the Worldly Philosophy?" — a question mark
  deliberately implying a change in economics' nature, not a eulogy

---

## Chapter I: Introduction

### The Paradox of the Great Economists

- The great economists were, by schoolbook standards, **nobodies**: no armies,
  no empires, no history-making decisions, no national heroism
- Yet their work was "more decisive for history than many acts of statesmen
  who basked in brighter glory"
- They worked quietly as scholars — but "left in their train shattered empires
  and exploded continents; they buttressed and undermined political regimes;
  they set class against class and even nation against nation"
- Not because they plotted mischief — because of the **extraordinary power
  of their ideas**

> "The ideas of economists and political philosophers, both when they are right
> and when they are wrong, are more powerful than is commonly understood.
> Indeed the world is ruled by little else. Practical men, who believe themselves
> to be quite exempt from any intellectual influences, are usually the slaves of
> some defunct economist. Madmen in authority, who hear voices in the air, are
> distilling their frenzy from some academic scribbler of a few years back."
> — **Lord Keynes**

### Economics as Exciting, Not Dull

- Common misconception: economics is cold, difficult, best left to experts
- Reality: "the science that has sent men to the barricades"
- Unlike pure philosophy, economic ideas couldn't be tested in a laboratory —
  they played out in society itself; **mistakes were calamitous, not academic**
- The great economists "took the whole world as their subject" in bold attitudes:
  angry, desperate, hopeful
- Their evolution of **heretical opinions into common sense** and exposure of
  **common sense as superstition** = the gradual construction of the
  intellectual architecture of contemporary life

### Who Were These Men?

- An extraordinarily motley group: philosopher and madman, cleric and
  stockbroker, revolutionary and nobleman, aesthete, skeptic, tramp
- Wildly contradictory personal views:
  - One was a lifelong advocate of women's rights; another called women
    demonstrably inferior
  - One (very rich) urged abolition of riches; another (quite poor)
    disapproved of charity
  - Several held this was the best of all possible worlds; several devoted
    their lives to proving it wasn't
- Their **common denominator**: shared fascination with the world's complexity,
  disorder, and the cruelty it masked in sanctimony
- All absorbed in **how man creates material wealth, then treads on his
  neighbor to get a share of it**

### The "Worldly Philosophy" Defined

- Called **worldly philosophers** because they embraced "the most worldly of
  all man's activities — his drive for wealth" within a philosophical system
- Their act of faith: that seemingly unrelated threads (pauper, speculator,
  greengrocer, mob) could be woven into a **single tapestry** — seen at
  sufficient distance, the milling world resolves into an orderly progression
- This faith turned out to be **justified**: once economists unfolded their
  patterns, each actor was understood to play a necessary role in the human drama
- The search for **order and meaning in social history** is the heart of economics
  and the central theme of this book

### Why No Economists for 6,000 Years?

- **Adam Smith** lived at the time of the American Revolution — yet 6,000 years
  of recorded history had produced no worldly philosopher
- Man struggled with economic survival since before the Pharaohs, producing
  philosophers, scientists, statesmen, historians — but **no economists**
- Reason: understanding must wait until Chapter II — the world before Smith
  was one in which an economist would have been "not only unnecessary,
  but impossible"

---

## Chapter II: The Economic Revolution

### The Survival Problem

- Man has always faced survival **as a social group**, not as an individual
- The problem: man is not an ant with inborn social instincts — he is
  **self-centered by nature**, yet his weak physique forces cooperation
- His inner drives "constantly threaten to disrupt his social working partnerships"
- In primitive society, this tension is resolved by **environmental pressure**:
  starvation threat pushes communities to cooperate (e.g., Eskimos)
- Under less dire conditions, cooperation runs on **kinship and reciprocity**
  - **Elizabeth Marshall Thomas** in her book on the **African Bushmen**:
    a gemsbok is divided among relatives until "no person eats more than
    any other"

### The Fragility of Advanced Society

- In modern communities, environmental pressure and kinship obligations vanish
- When 2/3 of the population never touches earth, mines, or factories, and
  kinship claims disappear — perpetuating human society becomes a
  **"remarkable social feat"**
- Vivid illustration of fragility: if farmers stop planting, railroadmen become
  bookkeepers, or miners disappear — "industrial life would soon become
  hopelessly disorganized"
- Every day, modern society faces potential breakdown **not from nature but
  from sheer human unpredictability**

### Three Solutions to the Survival Problem

Man has found only three ways to ensure social continuity:

1. **Tradition** — tasks handed down generation to generation by custom
   - Ancient Egypt (per Adam Smith): "every man was bound by a principle of
     religion to follow the occupation of his father"
   - India: occupations assigned by **caste** until recently
   - Much of the unindustrialized world still born to social task

2. **Command (Authority)** — whip of authoritarian rule directs labor
   - The pyramids were NOT built by enterprising contractors following
     self-interest
   - Soviet Five Year Plans did NOT follow hand-me-down custom
   - Both Russia and ancient Egypt were **Command societies** —
     economic survival enforced by edicts and penalties

3. **The Market System** — the revolutionary third solution (see below)

### Why Tradition and Command Needed No Economists

- Countless centuries ran on tradition or command alone
- Despite astonishing economic diversity (dried codfish as money, immovable
  stones as currency, communistic or ritualistic distribution) — as long as
  societies ran by custom or command, they needed no economists
- Theologians, political theorists, statesmen, philosophers, historians —
  yes. Economists — no.

### The Market System as Revolutionary Puzzle

- The **market system**: society assures its own continuance by allowing each
  individual to do exactly as he sees fit — provided he follows one rule:
  **do what is to his best monetary advantage**
- Lure of **gain** (not tradition, not authority) steers society's labor
- Paradox: each person free to go wherever acquisitive nose directs,
  yet the interplay of individuals results in **all necessary tasks getting done**
- This was "paradoxical, subtle, and difficult" — unlike tradition or command,
  it was **not at all obvious** that self-interest could sustain a society
- The market system called forth the economists — someone had to explain
  how this puzzle worked

### The Market System as the Most Important Revolution

- The transition to the market system was "the most important revolution,
  from the point of view of shaping modern society, that ever took place —
  fundamentally more disturbing by far than the French, the American,
  or even the Russian Revolution"
- Until the market idea gained acceptance, there was no puzzle to explain —
  and no economics
- Men were "not at all sure that the market system was to be viewed without
  suspicion, distaste, and distrust"
- Abandoning the security of tradition and command for the "dubious and
  perplexing workings of the market system" required **nothing short of
  a revolution**

### Vignettes of the Pre-Market World

**France, 1305 — A Medieval Fair**
- Traveling merchants with armed guard, exotic goods: silks, spices, furs,
  hides from the Levant, Scandinavia, Arabia
- Business records are crude notebooks: "Owed ten gulden by a man since
  Whitsuntide. I forgot his name."
- Calculations in **Roman numerals**; long division a mystery; zero not
  clearly understood
- Scale: all goods crossing France via the **Saint Gothard pass** in a year
  (over the first suspension bridge in history) would not fill a modern
  freight train; all Venetian fleet merchandise would not fill one steel freighter

**Germany, ~1550 — Andreas Ryff's Journey**
- Merchant **Andreas Ryff**, bearded and fur-coated, writes home from 30 markets
- Troubled by saddle burn — and more: stopped ~every 10 miles for customs tolls
- Between Basle and Cologne: **31 separate levies**
- [Notes continue on following pages — batch ends here]

